               <note xml:id="d2e7925" n="5"> This is an exact
                            transliteration into Latin from the Greek <span xml:lang="checkme"></span>, short from <span xml:lang="checkme"></span>, see vol. 3, Introduction 2.3.2.2, p. 14. It is
                            the Greek spelling of this name in LXX, see H. &amp; R. Suppl.
                        45.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e7935" n="6"> This is a variant reading, see previous note. The
                            additional h fits the transliteration of the name in the Vulgate in Num
                            1:10, which is also the product of Jerome. Which is the correction of
                            which is hard to decide here.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e7942" n="7"> In Latin - patriarcha. On this title see Introduction
                        3.1.3.5.1.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e7965" n="8"> This
                            is the year to which this letter of Jerome is dated. According to
                            Graetz, he should be dated to 365-85, see Jacobs, Die Institution des jüdischen Patriarchen, 206 and Introduction
                            7.4.6.</note>
